<paragraph blockId="5.[491,1520,1904,2032]" lastBlockId="7.[491,1527,229,357]" lastPageId="7" lastPageNumber="489" pageId="5" pageNumber="487">
Diagnosis (Female) — Prodorsum with even reticulations and short serrate setae, opisthosoma between setae 
<emphasis box="[648,673,1938,1962]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="487">c1</emphasis>
and 
<emphasis box="[727,756,1938,1962]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="487">d1</emphasis>
and 
<emphasis box="[807,836,1938,1962]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="487">d1</emphasis>
and 
<emphasis box="[887,912,1938,1962]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="487">e1</emphasis>
wrinkled with a few V-shaped folds behind setae 
<emphasis box="[1451,1476,1938,1962]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="487">e1</emphasis>
, reticulations mediodorsally, with 7 pairs of short, serrate marginal setae (including 
<emphasis box="[1385,1406,1973,1997]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="487">f2</emphasis>
) and 3 pairs of dorsocentral setae apparently smooth (
<figureCitation box="[1001,1087,2008,2032]" captionStart="Figure 4" captionStartId="6.[119,186,1916,1937]" captionTargetBox="[213,1390,255,1848]" captionTargetId="figure-2@6.[193,1403,249,1863]" captionTargetPageId="6" captionText="Figure 4 Brevipalpus californicus(Banks) – Female: A – dorsal view; B – ventral view; C – spermatheca; D – tarsus II, the arrows indicate the two distal solenidia." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5399538" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5399538/files/figure.png" pageId="5" pageNumber="487">Fig 4A</figureCitation>
); rostrum extends to about middle of femur I; tarsus II with 2 solenidia distally (
<figureCitation box="[971,1057,229,253]" captionStart="Figure 4" captionStartId="6.[119,186,1916,1937]" captionTargetBox="[213,1390,255,1848]" captionTargetId="figure-2@6.[193,1403,249,1863]" captionTargetPageId="6" captionText="Figure 4 Brevipalpus californicus(Banks) – Female: A – dorsal view; B – ventral view; C – spermatheca; D – tarsus II, the arrows indicate the two distal solenidia." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5399538" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5399538/files/figure.png" pageId="7" pageNumber="489">Fig 4D</figureCitation>
); genital shield with large reticulations, connected to form transverse bands, and ventral shield with smaller reticulations also forming transverse bands (
<figureCitation box="[691,775,299,323]" captionStart="Figure 4" captionStartId="6.[119,186,1916,1937]" captionTargetBox="[213,1390,255,1848]" captionTargetId="figure-2@6.[193,1403,249,1863]" captionTargetPageId="6" captionText="Figure 4 Brevipalpus californicus(Banks) – Female: A – dorsal view; B – ventral view; C – spermatheca; D – tarsus II, the arrows indicate the two distal solenidia." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5399538" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5399538/files/figure.png" pageId="7" pageNumber="489">Fig 4B</figureCitation>
); spermatheca terminates into a round vesicle with a crown of short finger-like projections, vesicle with a semi-lunar “bubble” internally (
<figureCitation box="[1248,1332,333,357]" captionStart="Figure 4" captionStartId="6.[119,186,1916,1937]" captionTargetBox="[213,1390,255,1848]" captionTargetId="figure-2@6.[193,1403,249,1863]" captionTargetPageId="6" captionText="Figure 4 Brevipalpus californicus(Banks) – Female: A – dorsal view; B – ventral view; C – spermatheca; D – tarsus II, the arrows indicate the two distal solenidia." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5399538" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5399538/files/figure.png" pageId="7" pageNumber="489">Fig 4C</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
